  1. To compress, or not to compress. Thatâs the question. Letâs focus on the big data file labevents.csv.gz. Compare compressed gz file size to the uncompressed file size. Compare the run times of zcat < ~/mimic/hosp/labevents.csv.gz | wc -l versus wc -l labevents.csv. Discuss the trade off between storage and speed for big data files. (Hint: gzip -dk < FILENAME.gz > ./FILENAME. Remember to delete the large labevents.csv file after the exercise.)

Answer:

gzip -dk < ~/mimic/hosp/labevents.csv.gz > ./labevents.csv
ls -l labevents.csv
ls -l ~/mimic/hosp/labevents.csv.gz
-rw-r--r--@ 1 jennynguyen  staff  13730083993 Jan 18 19:34 labevents.csv
-rw-rw-r--@ 1 jennynguyen  staff  1939088924 Jan  5  2023 /Users/jennynguyen/mimic/hosp/labevents.csv.gz

The file size for the compressed file labevents.csv.gz is 1.9GB, while the file size for the uncompressed file labevents.csv is 13.7GB. The file size for the uncompressed file is much larger and takes up more space than the file size for the compressed file.

time zcat < ~/mimic/hosp/labevents.csv.gz | wc -l
 118171368

real    0m18.213s
user    0m22.282s
sys 0m1.740s
time wc -l labevents.csv
 118171368 labevents.csv

real    0m5.809s
user    0m4.241s
sys 0m1.309s

The run time of zcat < ~/mimic/hosp/labevents.csv.gz | wc -l was around 18 seconds, while the run time of wc -l labevents.csv was around 6 seconds. Although the file size of the compressed file was smaller, it did take longer to run the command. In contrast, the file size of the uncompressed file was large, but the run time for the command was much faster. Thus, there are trade-offs between having a small, compressed file that runs slower versus a large, uncompressed file that runs faster.

Q4. Whoâs popular in Pride and Prejudice

  1. You and your friend just have finished reading Pride and Prejudice by Jane Austen. Among the four main characters in the book, Elizabeth, Jane, Lydia, and Darcy, your friend thinks that Darcy was the most mentioned. You, however, are certain it was Elizabeth. Obtain the full text of the novel from http://www.gutenberg.org/cache/epub/42671/pg42671.txt and save to your local folder.
wget -nc http://www.gutenberg.org/cache/epub/42671/pg42671.txt

Explain what wget -nc does. Do not put this text file pg42671.txt in Git. Complete the following loop to tabulate the number of times each of the four characters is mentioned using Linux commands.

Answer: The wget -nc command, when run in terminal, allows the user to download files from the Internet, non-interactively. The -nc option prevents the user from overwriting files when a shell redirect is used.

# wget -nc http://www.gutenberg.org/cache/epub/42671/pg42671.txt
for char in Elizabeth Jane Lydia Darcy
do
  echo $char:
  grep -o $char ./pg42671.txt | wc -l
done
Elizabeth:
     634
Jane:
     293
Lydia:
     170
Darcy:
     417
  1. Whatâs the difference between the following two commands?
echo 'hello, world' > test1.txt

and

echo 'hello, world' >> test2.txt

Answer: Using > will direct the output from the command into the file. Using >> will append the output from the command to the file.

  1. Using your favorite text editor (e.g., vi), type the following and save the file as middle.sh:
#!/bin/sh
# Select lines from the middle of a file.
# Usage: bash middle.sh filename end_line num_lines
head -n "$2" "$1" | tail -n "$3"

Using chmod to make the file executable by the owner, and run

chmod u+x middle.sh
./middle.sh pg42671.txt 20 5
Editor: R. W. Chapman

Release date: May 9, 2013 [eBook #42671]

Language: English

Explain the output. Explain the meaning of "$1", "$2", and "$3" in this shell script. Why do we need the first line of the shell script?

Answer: The output includes lines from the middle of the text file pg42671.txt. "$1", "$2", and "$3" are positional parameters that denote the order that the arguments are passed to the shell script, with "$1" representing the first argument, "$2" representing the second argument, and so on. We need the first line of the shell script to specify what command is to be run and what positions the arguments should be placed in for the command to run as desired. In this first line, head will print out the first few lines of a file, but -n "$2" specifies that we want head -20 to print out the first 20 lines of the file, since 20 is the second argument. pg42671.txt is the first argument, so $1 refers to pg42671.txt as the file that we want to select lines from. This output is then piped into tail -5 since 5 is the third argument, which prints out the last 5 lines of the first 20 lines of the file.

The last command shows a list of the last log-ins of users and terminals, starting from the most recent time. This command is piped into the head command, which displays only the first few lines of the list. The output displays the log-in name, the terminal name, the start and stop time of each session, and the duration of each session.

The echo {con,pre}{sent,fer}{s,ed} command prints all of the words that start with âcon-â or âpre-â, are followed by â-sent-â or â-fer-â, and end with â-sâ or â-edâ.

time sleep 5

real    0m5.007s
user    0m0.000s
sys 0m0.001s

The time sleep 5 command shows that it took 5 seconds to run the sleep 5 command. The sleep 5 command suspends execution for 5 seconds.

history | tail

The history | tail command, when run in terminal, shows a list of commands that were previously executed, with the tail command displaying only the last few lines of the list, which corresponds to the most recent commands executed.
